  "market_context": "After midnight open, price puts in a Judas swing higher into the London session high. ES and NQ are displayed side-by-side on the 1-hour chart, with prior sell-side liquidity resting at lows around 4798 (ES) and 16940 (NQ) as the draw on liquidity.",
  "key_observation": "At the London high, ES takes out the prior swing high while NQ fails to take its corresponding high, creating a bearish SMT divergence between the two correlated indices that acts as confluence for a reversal lower into sell-side liquidity.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify the directional bias — looking for a reversal/downside move to sell-side liquidity after a Judas push up from the midnight open into London session high.",
    "Step 2: Mark the London high on both ES and NQ and observe ES takes the high while NQ does not, forming a bearish SMT divergence.",
    "Step 3: Trust the SMT as a confluence to the reversal, anticipating price will continue lower and that the London high will not be touched again.",
    "Step 4: Watch price deliver lower and confirm it reaches the prior sell-side liquidity lows on both ES and NQ.",
    "Step 5: Note that SMT alone is not the reason for the reversal — structure and a bullish PD array failing to be respected aligned with the SMT to validate the short."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price reversed from the London high and reached the targeted sell-side liquidity lows on both ES and NQ, confirming the SMT-based short thesis.",
  "lessons": "SMT divergence is a confluence, not a standalone signal. It must align with higher-time-frame levels (session highs/lows, PDH/PDL) and structure for it to validate a reversal; the most relevant SMTs are those that occur at key liquidity levels.",
